{"title_page": "Christopher Evans (businessman)", "text_new": "{{other people||Christopher Evans (disambiguation){{!}}Christopher Evans}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sir Christopher Evans\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Christopher Thomas Evans\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1957|11|29|df=y}}<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood]]|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink=Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1353|ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Port Talbot]], Wales\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| nationality  = British\n| residence    = \n| education    = \n| alma mater   = [[Imperial College London]]<br/> [[University of Hull]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| title        = \n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = \n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| networth     = \u00a3158 million (2006)\n| spouse       = married\n| children     = 4\n| parents      = \n| relations    = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Christopher Thomas Evans''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 29 November 1957) is a Welsh [[biotechnology]] entrepreneur.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Thomas Evans was born in 1957, in [[Port Talbot]], to Cyril and Jean Evans. He was educated in [[microbiology]] at [[Imperial College London]] then obtained a PhD from the [[University of Hull]], followed by a research fellowship at the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name=\"burke\"/>\n\n==Career==\nEvans runs Merlin Biosciences (founded 1996), which manages investments in the biotechnology industry. He was the founder of [[Chiroscience]] (now merged with [[Celltech]]), [[Celsis]], [[Enzymatix]], and over 20 other life sciences based companies during his career.\n\nSetting up Arthurian Ltd, it successfully bid to run the [[Wales Life Sciences Investment Fund]], a \u00a3100 million 50/50 joint venture life sciences investment fund created to attract business to Wales. The fund has invested in and provided grants to [[ReNeuron]], in which Evans has also invested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-24355533|title=\u00a350m investment fund to be examined|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=25 January 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nTwice elected \"Cambridge Businessman of the Year\", he was awarded the OBE in 1995 and knighted in 2001.\n\nHe made a \u00a31 million loan to the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] during 2005. He was appointed a Honorary [[Fellow]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=List of Fellows|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/people-council-committees/the-fellowship/list-of-fellows}}</ref> of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]]<ref name=\"auto\"/> in 2005. In March of that year, he was appointed by [[Gordon Brown]] to the [[UK Stem Cell Initiative]]. He was arrested on 20 September 2006 as part of police enquiries into the \"[[Cash for Peerages]]\" allegations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5366858.stm|title=Profile: Sir Christopher Evans|date=21 September 2006|accessdate=25 January 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> but on 19 July 2007 the [[UK]] [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that there was insufficient evidence to bring the case to court.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n==Personal life==\nResident in [[Bibury]], in the [[Sunday Times Rich List 2006]] Evans was listed in 364th place with an estimated fortune of \u00a3158 million. He has a wife and four grown children. As a boy, he attended the St Joseph's school in Port Talbot. In July 2018, jewellery and family heirlooms worth more than \u00a31 million were stolen from his home in the Cotswolds. Evans offered a \"substantial\" reward for information leading to the thieves' conviction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/biotech-tycoon-sir-chris-evans-puts-up-reward-to-find-thieves-who-took-1m-jewellery-r3kvh8m2t|title=Biotech tycoon Sir Chris Evans puts up reward to find thieves who took \u00a31m jewellery|last=Wood|first=Vincent|date=2018-08-01|work=The Times|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20031218171205/http://www.merlin-biosciences.com/People/VentureTeam.asp Merlin Biosciences - Brief biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110202130505/http://sirchristopherevans.com/ Personal Profile page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Port Talbot]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hull]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the pharmaceutical industry]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Bibury]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Christopher Evans (disambiguation){{!}}Christopher Evans}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sir Christopher Evans\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Christopher Thomas Evans\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1957|11|29|df=y}}<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood]]|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink=Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1353|ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Port Talbot]], Wales\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  = \n| nationality  = British\n| residence    = \n| education    = \n| alma mater   = [[Imperial College London]]<br/> [[University of Hull]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| title        = \n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = \n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| networth     = \u00a3158 million (2006)\n| spouse       = married\n| children     = 4\n| parents      = \n| relations    = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Christopher Thomas Evans''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 29 November 1957) is a Welsh [[biotechnology]] entrepreneur.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Thomas Evans was born in 1957, in [[Port Talbot]], to Cyril and Jean Evans. He was educated in [[microbiology]] at [[Imperial College London]] then obtained a PhD from the [[University of Hull]], followed by a research fellowship at the [[University of Michigan]].<ref name=\"burke\"/>\n\n==Career==\nEvans runs Merlin Biosciences (founded 1996), which manages investments in the biotechnology industry. He was the founder of [[Chiroscience]] (now merged with [[Celltech]]), [[Celsis]], [[Enzymatix]], and over 20 other life sciences based companies during his career.\n\nSetting up Arthurian Ltd, it successfully bid to run the [[Wales Life Sciences Investment Fund]], a \u00a3100 million 50/50 joint venture life sciences investment fund created to attract business to Wales. The fund has invested in and provided grants to [[ReNeuron]], in which Evans has also invested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-24355533|title=\u00a350m investment fund to be examined|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=25 January 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nTwice elected \"Cambridge Businessman of the Year\", he was awarded the OBE in 1995 and knighted in 2001.\n\nHe made a \u00a31 million loan to the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] during 2005. He was appointed a Honorary [[Fellow]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=List of Fellows|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/people-council-committees/the-fellowship/list-of-fellows}}</ref> of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]]<ref name=\"auto\"/> in 2005. In March of that year, he was appointed by [[Gordon Brown]] to the [[UK Stem Cell Initiative]]. He was arrested on 20 September 2006 as part of police enquiries into the \"[[Cash for Peerages]]\" allegations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5366858.stm|title=Profile: Sir Christopher Evans|date=21 September 2006|accessdate=25 January 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> but on 19 July 2007 the [[UK]] [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that there was insufficient evidence to bring the case to court.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n==Personal life==\nResident in [[Bibury]], in the [[Sunday Times Rich List 2006]] Evans was listed in 364th place with an estimated fortune of \u00a3158 million. He has a wife and four grown children. As a boy, he attended the St Joseph's school in Port Talbot. In July 2018, jewellery and family heirlooms worth more than \u00a31 million were stolen from his home in the Cotswolds. Evans offered a \"substantial\" reward for information leading to the thieves' conviction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/biotech-tycoon-sir-chris-evans-puts-up-reward-to-find-thieves-who-took-1m-jewellery-r3kvh8m2t|title=Biotech tycoon Sir Chris Evans puts up reward to find thieves who took \u00a31m jewellery|last=Wood|first=Vincent|date=2018-08-01|work=The Times|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20031218171205/http://www.merlin-biosciences.com/People/VentureTeam.asp Merlin Biosciences - Brief biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110202130505/http://sirchristopherevans.com/ Personal Profile page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Port Talbot]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial Co